South Africa s net domestic short-term loans increased by R10.5 billion in November, according to the latest provisional figures on loan, national revenue fund receipts/payment, and cash balances as at November 30, released by the National Treasury. Net domestic long-term loans inclusive of redemptions and repo transactions increased by R13.55 billion, National Treasury said in a statement. National revenue fund receipts of R226 million were recorded, mainly in respect of revaluation profits on foreign currency transactions and premiums received on bond transactions. Government s cash balances increased by R6.336 billion to R207 billion. The South African Reserve Bank accounts, sterilisation, and foreign currency deposits amounted to R166 billion. Cash balances with commercial banks amounted to R41 billion, the Treasury said. More detailed information on the provisional figures would be included in the monthly statements of the national revenue, expenditure, and borrowing to be released on December 30. African News Agency (ANA)